Bountied air purifier had a dirty data secret [https://fulu-foundation.ghos=
t.io/r/5d1ebf72?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b]












By Kevin O'Reilly =E2=80=A2 3 Apr 2026


View in browser [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/71288e42?m=3Db503a08a-c=
4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b]




View in browser [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/ce9a9b25?m=3Db503a08a-c=
4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b]















Image credit: Dominik Z=C3=BCrner











=C2=A0











=C2=A0















I wonder how much you think about your data when you decide to buy an IoT d=
evice.

If you=E2=80=99ve been watching Louis=E2=80=99 channel for long enough, you=
 probably think about it more than the average consumer. Maybe it=E2=80=99s=
 your first thought. Maybe it=E2=80=99s something you weigh against the pos=
sible benefits that the device might bring to your life.

If you don=E2=80=99t think about it at all, a recent finding by cybersecuri=
ty researcher Dominik Z=C3=BCrner suggests that these ideas should probably=
 come up sooner. Dominik found that Molekule air purifiers, which we target=
ed with a bounty [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/4c8044d8?m=3Db503a08a-=
c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] last fall, had vulnerabilities [https://fulu-f=
oundation.ghost.io/r/9a8aa9cc?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] tha=
t would allow =E2=80=9Can unauthenticated attacker [to] access Molekule=E2=
=80=99s AWS IoT Core MQTT broker and subscribe to wildcard topics, receivin=
g real-time device shadow updates from approximately 100,000 deployed IoT d=
evices globally.=E2=80=9D

You don=E2=80=99t need to be a cybersecurity expert to know that =E2=80=9Cr=
eceiving real-time device shadow updates from approximately 100,000 IoT dev=
ices globally=E2=80=9D is not a good thing. Those updates included device o=
wners=E2=80=99 WiFi network names, MAC addresses unique to each device, dev=
ice names, and sensor readings.











=C2=A0




[https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/f44842b4?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f9=
8315f6032b]





Cyber vulnerabilities can lead to harm IRL

To me, any knowledge that my data has been unduly accessed is a violation i=
n its own right. But the Molekule vulnerability could lead to real-life har=
m if exploited by the wrong party. Tracking usage data could help a black h=
at hacker recognize when a user is or isn=E2=80=99t home. Knowledge of filt=
er status combined with an easily identifiable WiFi name=E2=80=94such as on=
e Colorado-based dentist=E2=80=99s office that Dominik found in the logs=E2=
=80=94could be leveraged to launch a hyper-targeted phishing scheme.

Dominik, who is a professional security analyst, will sometimes look under =
the hood of consumer devices in his free time. After hearing about our boun=
ty [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/71e214a5?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68=
-f98315f6032b] targeting Molekule=E2=80=99s effort to prevent owners from u=
sing third-party filters, he borrowed his friends air purifier and got to w=
ork. Once he found the issue, he notified the company, in line with respons=
ible disclosure practices.

Molekule=E2=80=99s response had some bugs as well. First, Dominik said, the=
y offered him a $5,000 bounty for his finding. That=E2=80=99s a good thing=
=E2=80=94bug bounties can be an effective way to reward cybersecurity resea=
rchers for identifying problems that could lead to consumer harm so that co=
mpanies can fix them before any damage is done.

The problem was that the company asked him to sign an overly-strong NDA tha=
t =E2=80=9Cbasically prevent[ed] me from ever discussing this vulnerability=
, even after a fix,=E2=80=9D Dominik wrote in a GitHub post [https://fulu-f=
oundation.ghost.io/r/a734b4f7?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b]. Th=
is is not how responsible disclosure should work,=E2=80=9D so he declined t=
he bounty.

According to Dominik, after he provided Molekule with details on how he gai=
ned access to user data, the company did not respond to his requests for up=
dates until he posted the vulnerability 90 days after his initial disclosur=
e. Shortly after that, the company responded and =E2=80=9Cmischaracterized =
the vulnerability as requiring =E2=80=98wrongful registration=E2=80=99 and =
claimed it would constitute =E2=80=98criminal trespass.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D M=
ischaracterization or not, the company also acknowledged that it had implem=
ented a patch.

=E2=80=9CIt wouldn=E2=80=99t have been hard for them to be helpful througho=
ut this process,=E2=80=9D Dominik told me. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not trying =
to do anything other than make sure their users are secure. Just be nice.=
=E2=80=9D


We can=E2=80=99t take good behavior for granted

Being nice=E2=80=94or at least not being evil [https://fulu-foundation.ghos=
t.io/r/359ff2e8?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b]=E2=80=94is a good=
 place to start. But our bounty program has already provided two reasons no=
t to assume that IoT manufacturers are going to have our best interests at =
heart. In addition to Dominik=E2=80=99s cybersecurity concern, Nest bounty =
[https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/00ee6c51?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f9=
8315f6032b] winner Cody Kociemba found that first and second generation Goo=
gle Nest devices were phoning home with troves of user [https://fulu-founda=
tion.ghost.io/r/e5cbaphishing@pot?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] data aft=
er thermostat owners lost access to their smart features.

Protecting the cybersecurity research done by Dominik, Cody, and countless =
other public interest minded hackers is another reason that Sec. 1201 of th=
e Digital Millennium Copyright Act needs reform. Whether on purpose or by a=
ccident, there is no guarantee that manufacturers will make sure that our d=
ata and our online lives are protected. Circumventing digital locks will al=
ways be necessary to ensure that they are. Researchers shouldn=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to risk facing a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a $500,000 =
fine to verify that consumers are protected.

At the end of the day, ownership is about knowledge as much as it is about =
control. That=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99re continuing to push for policies t=
hat protect researchers just as much as they protect the fixers, tinkerers =
and owners of the digital devices that have become so central to our lives.



















